Flight Data Project

Albert Perez

11/4/2021

Airline Travel Exploratory Data Analysis Project

Context

I am currently working for a fictional company called Paste Marketing which aims to help airline companies map out their data for stakeholders to help them generate business/data-driven decisions. Imagine an outside client hired us to find data that can help airlines decide whether we can find ways to increase customer satisfaction by analyzing the delay and arrival times. Our client works in a site in Washington and wants to know what our departure and arrival delay data dictates and how we can use it to improve customer experience on flights to California.

Purpose

This project will focus on flight time quality and how we can use the data to predict when we have the worst and best flights. It should help airlines decide how to boost creative processes during delays to keep customers satisfied during different periods.

Stakeholders

The stakeholders for this project are the airline companies which could potentially help them to push their marketing in WA and our client.

Data Preparation

The data was collected from the Bureau of Transportation Statistics Tran Stats search tool. It will be stored locally on my desktop for further use. It will be stored in the following data formats 2021_date.csv. The data can be classified as primary data as it generates the information right from the source.

Some information about the data that will help when visualizing the information.

The Airline will be classified under the OP_Unique_Carrier. Each airline has its own code. For this project, we will be using specific airlines in the US: 1. United Airlines-> UA 2. Delta Airlines -> DL 3. Southwest Airlines-> WN 4. JetBlue Airways -> B6 5. American Airlines -> AA 6. Hawaiian Airlines -> HA 7. Spirit Airlines -> NK 8. Frontier Airlines-> F9 9. Allegiant Airlines -> G4 10. Alaska Airlines -> AS

https://www.bts.gov/

Data Processing and Cleaning

The first step is to check for structural errors with the data set. After reviewing the Variables listed above, the data does not have any structural errors such as data type errors. Next, we duplicates, since the data has been merged from different data sets:

wa_flights <- all_flights %>%
  distinct() %>%
  filter(ORIGIN_STATE_ABR=="WA") %>%
  filter(OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER %in% c("AS", "G4", "AA", "DL", "F9", "HA", " B6", "WM", "NK", "UA"))

The data is complete and relevant to the problem I am trying to solve. Next would be to remove values that have a Null contained in their cells.

The table above shows that every row and column has a value.

This concludes the data cleaning process. We are ready to start the exploratory data analysis part of our project.

Long and Short Departure Delays

We will indicate that any time over 10 minutes will be long delays and everything else will be short

cal_flights <- cal_flights %>%
  mutate(long_short_dep = ifelse(DEP_DELAY< 10,"short", "long"))

dplyr::count(cal_flights, long_short_dep)

Analytic Approach

he analysis begins by understanding the variables in the data within the United States. First, we filtered the data to show only flights from Washington. Then, we filtered the data from the Washington flights that had a destination to California. We can use that information to measure how the datas density changes between the two. Both show a right skew to the data with a uni-modal distribution. The mean is greater for both distributions, confirmed based on the right skew of both histograms. We can see that the spread is less variable and can measure delays by the amount of time before leaving or arriving from the terminal. After separating the data into two different variables (long and short), we can see that delays have been kept to a minimum for flights heading to California. The largest amount of delays occurred in June 2020. The least number of delays occurred in December 2020 and January 2021. There is not much change between Departure and Arrival Delays between flights. The last information I wanted to share is the number of flights that have both departure and arrival delays. June 2020 has the highest number of delays in both arrivals and departures.
